  "slug": "full-english-breakfast",
  "title": "Full English breakfast",
  "subtitle": "Bacon, sausage, eggs, beans, toast, sequenced.",
  "excerpt": "The full plate: bacon, sausages, fried eggs, grilled tomato, mushrooms, baked beans, black pudding, and buttered toast, all hitting the table hot. The trick is sequencing: what goes on first, what goes on last, and where every pan sits while you build it. Serves two.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "The Edwardian English breakfast tradition is documented in the Book of Household Management (1861, Project Gutenberg #10136), as a sequence of separate cooked dishes brought to the table together. The contemporary all-on-one-plate shape settled mid-twentieth century in transport cafes and seaside boarding houses.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The full English is a plate of individually cooked things served together: back bacon, pork sausages, fried eggs, grilled tomatoes, mushrooms, baked beans, black pudding, and buttered toast. The result takes 25 minutes from a cold hob if the sequence is right."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Sequencing is everything. Sausages take longest, so they start first. Mushrooms and tomatoes go under the grill while the sausages brown. Bacon and black pudding go in the second half. Beans warm in their own pan. Eggs are last: two minutes. Toast pops at the last second."
          }
        ]
      },
